'''Thomas Laken''', born 3 March 1972,<ref name="bio">[http://parliament.gov.vu/Members/10th%20Legislature%20Biography/Hon.%20Thomas%20Laken.html Bio sheet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140428031643/http://parliament.gov.vu/Members/10th%20Legislature%20Biography/Hon.%20Thomas%20Laken.html |date=2014-04-28 }}, Parliament of Vanuatu</ref> is a [[Vanuatu]]an politician.

Self-employed in the shipping service, he later worked as a primary school teacher.<ref name="bio" /> He was first elected to the [[Parliament of Vanuatu]] as Independent MP for [[Tanna (island)|Tanna]], in the [[2012 Vanuatuan general election|2012 general election]].<ref name="bio" /> Prime Minister [[Sato Kilman]] appointed him as Minister of Justice and Social Welfare. In February 2013, Laken joined the [[Green Confederation]].<ref>[http://vanuatudaily.wordpress.com/2013/02/18/vanuatu-daily-news-digest-18-february-2013/ Vanuatu daily news digest | 18 February 2013]</ref> On 20 March, Thomas Laken and Minister for Ni-Vanuatu Business [[Marcellino Pipite]] crossed the floor to join the Opposition, along with six government backbenchers.<ref>[http://www.dailypost.vu/content/opposition-28-government-21 "Opposition 28, Government 21"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323095440/http://www.dailypost.vu/content/opposition-28-government-21 |date=2013-03-23 }}, ''Vanuatu Daily Post'', 21 March 2013</ref> Lacking a majority with which to govern, Kilman resigned the following day, before a motion of no confidence could be brought against him.<ref>[http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=74783 "Vanuatu Prime Minister, facing no confidence vote, resigns"], Radio New Zealand International, 21 March 2013</ref> New Prime Minister [[Moana Carcasses Kalosil]] (of the Green Confederation, the country's first Green Prime Minister) appointed him as Minister for Planning and Climate Change Adaptation.<ref>[http://www.dailypost.vu/content/nations-interest-first-carcasses "Nation's interest first: Carcasses‚Äù] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130329020142/http://www.dailypost.vu/content/nations-interest-first-carcasses |date=2013-03-29 }}, ''Vanuatu Daily Post'', 26 March 2013</ref> He lost office when Carcasses' government was ousted in a motion of no confidence on 15 May 2014, then resumed office when the new government of [[Joe Natuman]] was itself ousted in the same manner on 11 June 2015, and [[Sato Kilman]] became Prime Minister.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-06-12/vanuatu-announces-new-cabinet-after-new-pm-sato-kilman-elected/6541328 "Vanuatu announces new cabinet after new prime minister Sato Kilman is elected"], Australian Broadcasting Corporation, 12 June 2015</ref>

